# Unity OOP Design Guardrails

- Class names should state responsibility clearly; vague names such as `Manager`, `Helper`, `Util`, `System`, and `Handler` indicate growing responsibility.
- Do not use public mutable fields in Domain/Application models; preserve invariants through constructors, factories, or intention-revealing mutation methods.
- Expose collections as read-only views; if mutation is needed, use meaningful methods.
- Do not create an interface for every class automatically; define interfaces at the consumer side when a port, test seam, replaceable policy, or cross-layer boundary is needed.
- Prefer small policy/service composition over deep inheritance and base classes with optional behavior.
- For variants expected to grow, prefer policy, strategy, polymorphism, or validated config over large switch/if chains.
- Constructors should only assign dependencies and validate invariants; do not start IO, asset loading, event subscription, async work, or gameplay side effects.
- Static methods are acceptable only for pure helpers/value calculations; do not access runtime state, scene objects, services, or config through statics.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: State can be mutated from outside
public int Coins;

// GOOD: The invariant is protected inside the state object
public void Spend(CurrencyAmount price)
{
    if (price.Amount > Coins) throw new InvalidOperationException();
    Coins -= price.Amount;
}
```
